The Prague Stock Exchange is down at the end of trading
The Prague Stock Exchange has corrected its losses after the crash this morning.
Transactions in shares of the Czech Energy Company (<0xC4><0x8C>EZ) have reached almost half of the usual daily trading.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued to fall on Monday from the start of trading on Tuesday, when it fell almost six percent.
This time, the decline in Wall Street shares is behind the decline.
This is how the market reacted to the vote in the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the financial sector stabilisation plan there.
Falling Stocks in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall in stocks on Tuesday, although some of the losses were eventually cancelled over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock exchange index recorded a depreciation of almost four percent during the trading process, but later cancelled some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng China Enterprises Index fell 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but ultimately the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwanese stock market fell by 3.6 percent, according to the Taiwanese index.
“The timing of the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and affects the world’s financial markets,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said the U.S. legislators should immediately reopen negotiations and adopt a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will feel the consequences.
The Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which should have been spent <0x24>700 billion (almost 12 trillion kroons).
Legislators have thus ignored President Bush’s call to support the plan.
Bush said the plan would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the economy as a whole.
On Monday, U.S. stocks went through a bloodbath, and leading stock indices recorded the biggest fall in 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell by nearly seven percent, the last time it experienced a similar drop was in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the bill was not passed in the House of Representatives, the index began to fall free.
Congress Retreats: U.S. Government Could Pump <0x24>700 Billion into Banks
The top leaders of the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement and financial assistance to the US financial system.
This will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in negotiations to approve a rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the U.S. financial system in the amount of <0x24>700 billion (approximately 12 trillion kroons).
But there is no victory yet.
Congress will have to complete some of the details of the agreement before they can release the final form of the law and their vote.
The draft financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
This was reported to Reuters on Sunday by Barney Frank, the chairman of the Financial Institutions Committee.
Senate sources say the bill will probably be voted on Wednesday.
According to economists, there should be an announcement that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor in reviving the financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, there is a subsequent "sobering up".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We took a big step.
We have resolved our differences of opinion on what the form of the market stabilization package should be," said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat for the Bloomberg agency.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Legislators met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Saturday night to give a final form to the government fund.
This should buy off unsellable mortgages from financial corporations, placing financial corporations in serious losses and jeopardising the stability of the entire system.
“We are close to reaching a final agreement on a draft that will work and that should also be effective in the market.
The renovation plan still needs to be continued, but I think we are there," Paulson said.
Sign for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on the stock markets, which are falling heavily.
Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid said the legislators were trying to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before they start trading on Asian financial markets, where, due to the time zone, Congress’s decision could be the first to affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether the trial could be stopped at the last minute due to a problem.
The lawmakers hope that the bill will be approved in the coming days.
However, the law is still undergoing a number of changes.
The total amount earmarked for aid to the system shall be divided into two parts.
As President Bush has requested, the first <0x24>350 billion should be made available as soon as possible.
Congress, however, can block the release of the remaining amount, which is set at an additional <0x24>100 billion, and later at <0x24>350 billion, if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function.
Bush appreciates progress in talks
Although the President may veto this resolution, Congress may override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the core idea of the program remained to acquire funds to buy bad mortgage securities that had lost their value, as hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to repay their mortgage loans.
"We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
US President Bush is pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
Bush spokesman Tony Fratto said the president was satisfied with Saturday’s progress and appreciated “the bipartisan efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of Busy Dismissal Compensation
Christopher Dodd, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, said the legislators had agreed on the responsibility for the financial program, taxpayers’ protection from losses, the closure of the concessions, and the timing of the financing plan.
The new law also limits the so-called “busy” severance pay for directors participating in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The fund should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this and have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and that will benefit all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new instalments for mortgages it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly instalments of debtors and enabling them to keep their houses.
Marek: Spiritual Aid
According to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, the proposed draft is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
“It’s because you don’t know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be purchased.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government allocate losses to each other,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Marek, it is not so important whether the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week.
“It’s much more important that Congress decides this week whether it supports the plan and gives its blessings as soon as possible.
The spiritual importance of reaching an agreement that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at the moment," Marek said.
Duel on edge: MP3 players versus mobiles.
We help you choose
While almost all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can be used to make phone calls.
It seems clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are many reasons why you should buy a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
You’ll probably find it hard to get a high-end expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on vinyl records, but from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl records, you probably dream of such a turntable.
This is similar to travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to sell eight thousand crowns for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan is likely to find it difficult to accept a twenty-kroon market headset.
There are two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
There's a lot to choose from.
The lifespan of the batteries also counts
Some high-end music players can do much more than just play music, but also what most mobiles don’t do.
No other device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions of calling and texting, it can also play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera, and even navigate.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you’ll also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a little wonder, because no refrigerator can barbecue and no television can take photos.
There are also disadvantages to multi-functional mobile phones.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more times the display sends you to the charger.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy consumers.
Few mobile devices can play music for longer than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For low-cost mobile phones, you should be aware that they will not be playing for you for more than a few hours.
If you're even on a phone here and there, just get a charger for your workplace - this applies to more expensive appliances.
With MP3 players, you won’t have such a problem, even the worse ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with a single charge.
The following issue arises when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB socket and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few card readers can cope with the miniature memory cards used in mobile devices without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPods), you don’t need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
Most mobiles and players create a music library arranged in order based on the artist, album, genre name, or user rating, for example.
Some devices only depict a tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles know more
When choosing a specific equipment, ask about the battery life, memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output, and of course, the convenience of handling.
If music serves you primarily as a background and you listen to it only for a short period of time on the tram, for example, any MP3-playing mobile will suit you.
Any mobile device can do that.
You don’t even have to pay special attention to what music formats your mobile or player can use.
All of them can cope with MP3, and the vast majority of the music that reaches you will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most widely used, and the vast majority of devices also handle WMA music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and your iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the appropriate pages of the service provider (or other service provider) through the mobile internet and purchase the song or album.
This service in itself can be a compelling reason to purchase a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the service providers’ offerings are crappy and are usually limited to annual radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
It is generally assumed, however, that such a way of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you can feel your phone in your pocket while the forgotten MP3 player lies at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your earbuds with you or at least your hands-free speakerphones.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which almost all mobiles have, but only a few MP3 players.
For many, the biggest advantage of music mobiles will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 2,000 pounds.
Between <0x24>3,000 and <0x24>4,000, you can get a decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you are limited by the lack of a traditional earbud output.
The best and most technically equipped phones with conventional 3.5mm hole headphones can cost up to 15,000 crowns.
At the same time, the advantage of the players is, among other things, the ease of operation.
Managing the simplest - by no means necessarily the cheapest players (see our selection) can really cope with everyone.
Minimal function, the handling similar to a previously standard cassette tape recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no threat of collapsing in the form of accidentally turned on mobile internet, nor in terms of the subsequent huge bill for data transmission.
What device to choose
The cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have slots for removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
With the right card, it can cost up to 2,000 crowns.
But be careful.
Basic types support only cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can handle up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or irivert.
Based on the capacity (maximum 2 GB), you don’t have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you belong to the more demanding students, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, which makes the handling more convenient than the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, which has the same user interface for walkman-series mobile phones as MP3 players sold separately, is the farthest in the industry.
MP3 players of the above-mentioned brands can offer the same service in the same price range up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual service provider that forces classical providers to substantially reduce their prices.
Maybe it won't be like this for long.
On the Mobil.cz website we have written many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
Following the latest move by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation - for some Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple: there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, as we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are keen to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, who has previously stated on several occasions that there is no room for another service provider in the Czech Republic, often agrees with this.
Perhaps it is true that the classic operator with its own network is probably no longer very likely (however, it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is one more option - the virtual provider.
It was the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that led to a significant price reduction, to which classical service providers had to respond.
In the meantime, even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile came to the market, there were sounds similar to ours in Britain.
However, it has been proven that such providers have their place and can be truly successful.
However, we do not need to go too far for example.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the ability to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, it requires much less customers than a traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers around the world therefore tend to show up as low-cost – offering cheap calls and text messages, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
Tesco Mobile in the UK, for example, offers at least 50% cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move to bet on a target group as well.
This service is focused on men.
“Real men choose Mobilking—who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar idea to that in Poland can work for us.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, a spokesman for Vodafone, said: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but the talks in the Czech Republic do not seem very hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries of our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It has indirectly shown that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic do not share this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best to prevent any potential competitors from forming.
For some time now, the GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in launching a virtual service provider, which aims to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in providing our customers with not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual service provider will be available by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we do not think that there is a place for a full-fledged virtual service provider in the Czech market.
Unlike other markets, the Czech market is very special.
Until now, we have not been addressed by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," he told Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, from the Press Department of Telefónica 02.
The specific situation of the Czech market is also referred to by other operators.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in agreement with O2, added: “We have not yet recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business project on which to build further.”
And he added, “In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it’s unlikely that any virtual service provider will pop up.
At this point, we should have a concrete agreement on our table so that we can think in such a short term.”
Vodafone is focusing on fulfilling its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most rewarding for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build networks shared for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - in one string with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean a rise in competition, a fall in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competition to enter?
When service providers have something important, they are able to collaborate, as well, the hustle and bustle around the birth of the U:fon.
The biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was probably around the birth of T-Mobile’s U:fone.
This is evidenced by publicly available information on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
But right now U:fon is a good argument for why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: “The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the arrival of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be highly demanding."
Given the attitude of mobile operators, however, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is absolutely astonishing.
In the meantime, this is not just about the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
Only the Hungarian Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
However, the agency has a distinctive attitude towards the whole problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would only be possible after the contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure has been concluded.
So far, no such contracts have been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional service providers," said Kristián Chlapua, of the Foreign Relations Department of the Hungarian Competition Authority, in answer to our question.
Such a statement from the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, it is more than odd from an office that should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one can abuse their market position.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a fall in the price of mobile services."
However, pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the reduction of prices is probably not in the interest of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
In this case, it is truly shocking the very touching consistency of the reactions of the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
As with the gas stations, the exact same gas prices are probably the result of coincidence and fierce competition.
"The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers have a leading position, i.e. no proportionate greater responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are probably also missing for the telecom regulator," Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leader position is one of the many points of controversy.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator is in a leading position after that.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach – the virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
Therefore, it is necessarily dominant in a certain segment.
But even if this argument were not accepted, it should be at least a warning to <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators behave in a remarkably similar way.
In the meantime, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they encounter very similar barriers in negotiations with all service providers.
And shifting the responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a trick that is relatively common in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have seen this in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not carried out, although many experts hoped that the situation would improve.
Representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS should know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one is watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of fake virtual service provider, many of which are already operating in the Czech mobile networks, goes unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, which, however, are only partially public.
These are multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the selected ones.
The charm lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the service provider, ordering a large amount of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-purchase.
"If there were any cases that you are talking about, there could be a breach of contract that we would address and that could lead to the termination of our cooperation with the company in question," Martina Kemrová said.
But it is quite unlikely that news of such activity would not have reached the responsible people of mobile operators.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, there can be thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider can defend itself against such a procedure.
In fact, these companies make no negligible profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual service providers, they are not particularly threatened with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns about possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that their phones do not have the SIM card in their name, so they cannot have it fully as the general customers of mobile operators."
At least that’s what I think is weird.
There is also another question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they preventing the birth of a virtual operator?
It should be added that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has a relatively strong authority to expose such activity and if it does not want to, it should not be satisfied with the service providers’ explanation that they did not suspect any such activity and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable fall in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were established, classical service providers tried to prevent them more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was at these very moments in the developed countries that regulators intervened, which in no way defended the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Then, through formal measures or informal pressure, they created the first virtual service provider, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are handing the whole thing over to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competencies are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the service providers would allow the creation of a virtual mobile operator, <0xC3><0x9A>OHS would only find it difficult to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And we may not be able to call more expensively than the rest of Europe.
