Rats have feelings too.
A rat or a moth flees in the event of danger, does that mean that he feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals have emotions.
But how can we examine whether they feel the same when they behave like us?
In the Internet magazine "Edge", famous scientists have been publishing their articles for years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE looks at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?" in one of its series.
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as we look at other species and dissect the questions of perception, or consciousness in general, we come to a difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
Humans behave in a similar way, which leads some researchers to infer comparable subjective experiences.
However, I do not believe in that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult for us to transfer our own subjective experiences to the animals.
On the one hand, the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive/control functions).
This wide area is more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely absent in other organisms.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as knowing who we are, or being able to plan and make decisions, we can reasonably assume that humans are different even from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Because a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not dependent on language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may be like in the case of other animals.
If consciousness is not measurable as an internal and subjective thing, and because of special hardware it cannot be analyzed based on our own experience, then its research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my explanations relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The conscious processes of animals could be studied regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, this hypothesis, which was also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, relies more on neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may or may not be the same.
Interestingly, this hypothesis underscores the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What is the consequence of this in terms of emotions?
This is due to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activities.
What we call “fear” is, therefore, the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defensive system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies working memory.
In this way, emotions are closely related to those areas of the cerebral cortex that are specific to primates and especially to humans.
In addition to the linguistic character, perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with the help of words and grammar we are able to distinguish and categorize states so that we can describe them to others as well as ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that emotions are derived from simpler activities in the sensory areas of the cerebral cortex and the brain stem, as is Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in species-wide emotions.
In purely theoretical terms, I cannot deny this, but I find it unproven.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be fear in both cases: How can we check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in danger, does he feel fear too?
In my opinion, just a similar behavior is not proof of the same experience.
While neural comparisons help further: rats and humans have similar brain stems, cockroaches do not have brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for emotions?
And even if this could be proven in humans, how can we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have emotions.
However, I do not know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'm researching the emotional behavior of rats rather than their emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is promising at the neural level, as long as we measure the same in rats and humans.
As with rats, I don’t research language and consciousness, nor do I research emotions, because I don’t know if they exist.
For others, this may seem like a short-sighted attitude, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly hitting a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
