Eatonville, the first purely black city to integrate into the country, which was Zora Neale Hurston's childhood home, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guayavas, and two school towns without prison."
It's a pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison, and Ruby Dee have attended the annual Zora Festival. The Eatonville ceremony is held in honor of Harlem’s most famous female writer, Hurston.
Yet, in many respects, the city he describes and makes a tourist attraction, which is also included in the Florida Guidebook of the Federal Writers Project of the Crisis Age, is separate from its surroundings.
As independent, dignified, and self-absorbed as it was in the 1930s, Hurston wrote that city blacks in Florida were often unwilling to share their real thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing."
Even in the year the black presidential candidate, Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on the race issue, many here are distrustful of outsiders’ glances.
"We are very careful how our story is told," said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here her entire life and is a member of the oldest church in the city.
"You have to say it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historical model of blacks’ standpoint, but it is also a community of nearly 2,400 people, where poverty indicators reach twice the national average.
Partly a literary node and partly an example of the sometimes despised, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shade of oak trees.
It is not surprising, then, that the people here are both proud and defensive.
The picture of Eatonville has been important since Zora (this is how everyone calls Hurston).
In honest, strong dialect books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937) he presented his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida guidebook have transformed the city, which lies next to Route 17. This road leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in both life and literature, like a drum roller, introduced his readers to Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then explored the more confidential spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road, we find a modern public school with a white border on a brown background, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds, which are maintained by Howard Miller, although he can barely read or write."
He mentioned the widow’s new husband, Dash, and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells all kinds of drinks and whatever may be needed in the temporary accommodation.”
Thus, in a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with autonomy, but also illiteracy, remarrying, and sex.
Obviously, the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description did not really please everyone.
"Zora said things the way they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls, who Hurston made immortal by quoting the slippery songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, “Some people didn’t like it.”
Hurston is still remembered here as a living separated man who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a roaring Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes and wearing long pants in a city where people still take pride in their dignified dress.
"Most people were fascinated," Franklin said, "but a lot of people were grumpy."
"People were always happy to see Zora," Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair: "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were never re-published.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with much of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although she was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she previously lived.
There were no significant commemorations or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us," said Valerie Boyd, author of the 2003 Hurston biography, "Wrapped in a Rainbow."
