The victory over the road construction project helped to change the city’s image of itself.
An increasing number of people outside the city appeared, such as attorney Rachelle Munson, who began attending church here in 1993, and the locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was included in the National Historical List in 1998.
In 2006, a new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened on the rebuilt and beautified Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains the cuckoo egg of Florida: not exactly ten kilometers from downtown Orlando, but sometimes you feel like a suburban side street during summer rain; as small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Ninety percent of the population today is black.)
They are still cautiously welcomed by outsiders who come here in search of Eatonville's story and story.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things—such as Eatonville’s oldest fresco painted by a white man and depicted blacks working in the fields—should not be photographed.
In Eatonville, many, including confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red, fear that their separate communities will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival became more and more widespread, the pride of the hometown grew.
Young people in particular are increasingly looking at Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with its problems and everything, neither better nor worse, as proud, creative, diligent, foolish and confused as the other races and ethnic groups in America.
The words of Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after graduating from college to work for the local government or police that he believes need help.
