“I don’t take photos on stage because I want to present the artist from a personal side.” – Günther Bauer
There's no set, no rollers, no dancing shoes.
The great masters of flamenco are close to the body, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the ordinary man.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in intimate, distant moments, when we can observe a personal movement, grasp the depth of a captured gaze, or marvel at the beauty of the idle, yet expressive hand of the artist, who is about to perform on stage.
In the German photographic series Flamenco-people by Günther Bauer, he combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known everyday side of masters.
Through the photographs, the iconography of flamenco is presented from different perspectives.
The exhibition, which is part of Flamenco's Month of Photography, "reflects the flamenco's growing international importance every day," the creator said, adding that Flamenco-people could be "anyone, as the viewer discovers that these images do not depict artists in a typical way.
These people shot on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, cheerfulness to the stage... and captivate the audience.
Stage photography, however, is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personalities of the greats of flamenco with the help of the camera.”
At the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer embarked on a long journey in 1997, taking portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a disc camera.
These portraits evoke classical photography thanks to the camera and subject selection.
The use of various stylistic tools, however, breaks with traditional imagery and suggests modernity. The following idea faithfully reflects Bauer's vision of flamenco: "This is a music with traditional roots, however, that changes from day to day and is always fascinating."
It is not dance, not even singing or music in itself, but rather the personality and character of the artist charms the audience.
The guiding motif of the works to be seen in the El Photomata Gallery these days is the search for the encounter with the essence, the artistic varasz, which becomes visible through the way of perception, being and display.
Famous flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are the names of this collection of photographs that will feature some sixty artists.
The project also became a flamenco anthology, which will soon be the subject of an album featuring the portraits presented at the exhibition.
Two years ago, Bauer's passion for portraits prompted him to repeat the idea with the "Portraits of Veterans Athletes" series ("SportARTproject").
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different, the photographer adds: “I like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is portrait.
You meet people, people you don’t even know, or people who only take a few minutes to take a photo.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realise my ideas.
The exhibition entitled Flamenco-people, selected from contemporary flamenco portraits, can be viewed in the El Photomata Gallery at Calle de la Mata 20, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, until 16 October.
