Those who speak in their dreams
Some kids talk at night.
I’m not talking about those who wake up and tell the story of what happened to them that day, but about those who talk while they’re asleep.
The phenomenon may seem frightening at first, but in fact it is completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquism.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure they've told a lot of them he spoke at night.
In terms of its frequency, it can be completely rhabdomyosodical (for example, it occurs only once in a high fever illness) or more regular (daily, weekly or monthly) and usually the child does not remember anything the next day.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single trigger.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night awakenings, enuresis nocturna or sleepwalking, but this is not legal either.
As already mentioned, it can be a condition with a high fever, or even an accompanying condition of stress or increased excitement.
So far, it has been little studied.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It can be quiet, calm, or consist of incoherent words or grunts, but in contrast, it can also take the form of shouting, crying, or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist. The examination may reveal if there is no underlying problem causing great anxiety and thus may offer a solution.
As already mentioned, it is a benign phenomenon and consequently there is no cure for it unless it is accompanied by some other treatable form of sleep disorder (such as insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things you can do, and here are a few preventive measures:
