Blood is safe again.
Hema-Quebec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday. President Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Hema-Quebec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood donor societies in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain people’s trust, which was severely undermined by the blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood supply managed by the Red Cross Blood Service in Canada became infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general uproar, the Canadian government launched a formal investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, to clarify the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make proposals to avoid similar incidents in the future.
While Judge Krever was delayed in submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committee to design a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Commission carried out this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports resulted in the establishment of two blood supply services in Canada: one for Héma-Quebec, which serves Quebec, and the other for all the other provinces and the two territories, the Canadian Blood Society.
"When Héma-Quebec started its operations in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system," says Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the following years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we have managed to regain people's trust." Décary proudly states that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population considered Héma-Quebec to be reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that “trust is an extremely fragile thing.”
Hema-Quebec has been applying the precautionary principle since its establishment on 28 September 1998.
During this period, many cases of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been in charge of the company since its founding in 1998.
"We had no idea if this disease was transmitted through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, we should apply exclusionary measures. In this case, we were talking about Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes changes in the brain, and thus inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was undoubtedly established that the disease was transmitted through blood.
This incident convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that makes it possible to diagnose HIV more sensitively. This is the nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to detect the virus itself directly in the blood of blood donors, rather than the antibodies formed against the virus, on which the tests previously used were built.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood with our technical tools, the expert explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk of blood donors unknowingly infecting the blood stock was significantly reduced and this could not be detected.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of transmission of AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
In other words, this means that we would have to distribute 12 million blood products until someone becomes infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such an event to occur and someone to become infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that anyone can now accept or prescribe blood transfusions to restore health, says the No. 1 leader of Hema-Quebec.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
You never know what kind of new pathogen is entering the system.
After all, it was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood by a bite of an insect.
Therefore, we must be constantly on guard,” Dr. Décary continued, stressing that in addition to emergency reserves, Héma-Quebec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
“As the population ages, demands also increase.
Because anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population is also affecting the donor population, as the number of people in the network who are able to donate blood accounts for only 3% of the population of Quebec.
However, any healthy person aged at least 18 who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have visited a country that is plagued by malaria are not eligible to donate blood for a year.
“With this 3%, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare that we run out of supplies.
The number of blood donors, however, must be increased to the extent that the existing ones are getting older, because after a while they can no longer donate blood.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and persuade them to become regular blood donors.
“In today’s rushed world, one has barely an hour to go out and donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of <0x24>297 million, Héma-Quebec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which are almost exclusively used in severely burned people.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed, and frozen, and placed at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public stem cell bank.
Only the umbilical cord, which was once treated as medical waste, can be used to extract blood that is rich in stem cells, and thus also to treat serious diseases (such as leukemia).
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the inclusion of the thousandth sample of cord blood in our bank, and we plan to collect more than a thousand new samples every year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering these for organ transplants,” said Dr. Décary, who said that the umbilical cord blood removal program is very popular nowadays.
“Many mothers are saddened that they don’t have the opportunity to do so,” he said, “because Hema-Quebec is not in a position to make this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
