The psychology of overspending: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to issue more money, overvalue the goods.
The neuro-economic foundations of this known – and seemingly irrational – behavior have been uncovered by neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to be defeated in a type of competition such as the eBay auction, so they tend to pay too high a price.
The research attempted to map the neurological pattern of this "play" by means of experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers took part in a lottery, while the other group participated in a playful auction while examining the active brain areas of the subjects using the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction, in which an essential element is the over-bidding of the other party, the subcortical complex called striatum became active intensively when the game was lost.
This area of the brain, among many other functions, plays a role in the “self-rewarding” mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price hike can be explained by avoiding a fierce reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research team also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they were out of the game, they would be rewarded with another <0x24>15.
The third group, on the other hand, received <0x24>15 just before the auction, but members of the group lost that money in the event of a losing auction.
The only difference between the two groups was that they emphasized winning for one and losing for the other.
However, proving the neurologists’ hypothesis, members of the team playing against “loss” were willing to bet higher than the control and “winning” groups.
"These findings cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
Until now, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of winning and risk avoidance.
“Only neuroimaging techniques have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, and we have now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to Seek a Doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected with hepatitis in Hungary is estimated at 100,000, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is a common term for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, characterized by hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (for example, infected with food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travelers should be vaccinated against the A and B viruses, but there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints, nausea.
After this, jaundice on the skin and the whites of the eyes develops, the stools are light, the urine turns dark, healing can take up to two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die each year from the most serious form of the disease, hepatitis B liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receives medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis, liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening tests are very important.
In three groups, there are far more than average cases of these diseases: people who had undergone blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
There are currently 200 million people infected with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult a general practitioner if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
By recognizing the disease in time, the virus can be cured and eliminated from the body, thus eliminating infectivity and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first celebrated in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
Its purpose is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a painkiller that may have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment to study how faith in God affects people’s perception of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
In a rather bizarre study, 12 Catholics and the same number of atheists were subjected to electroshock while each was studying a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholics were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Thanks to technology scanning the human brain, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The study is the first in a series of research involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching a sparking device to the subject’s left hand, which provided the electroshock.
The researchers asked participants to look strongly at two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the Lady with Hermelin painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would create a kind of religious state among believers, while the image of da Vinci was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to have a soothing effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner machine, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive episodes while either looking at the religious theme or the general picture.
Catholics reported that when they saw the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe” as they were “cared for” and “silent, peace filled them.”
While viewing the religious-themed picture, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo’s work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who participated in the study himself, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, even for atheists, just find the right photo.
"We should find a picture of someone they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the findings.
“Exercising faith should, and in many cases will, change our personality,” Wright said.
After the great results, the only question is, if Leonardo or a painter of a similar caliber is shown a picture of a madonna to believers, what effect would that have on their pain control?
Would the sight of the quality of the Virgin Mary bring even better results?
