Smart Car Imitates the Flying of the Bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop collision avoidance technologies, if not by imitating obstacle detectors that occur in the natural world?
Bees, for example.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C, a bio-imitation car robot control system, a robotized minicar with bee-like qualities, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that eliminates all collisions.
While flying, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective shell, said Kazuhhiro Doi, technology PR and R&D brand manager at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the complex eye of the uterus, which can see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To replicate the complex function of the eye, the engineers used the idea of laser telemetry.
It identifies obstacles within a distance of 2 metres in a 180-degree field of vision before the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is instantly transformed into a collision avoidance operation.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and the robot immediately changes its direction, imitating the movements of the uterus, by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If that were not the case, the car-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
You need to react in an intuitive and immediate way, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shell, a layer within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibility for bees to bypass other bees, only rotational motion and acceleration and slowing down were used as an option available to the car robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, instinctive intelligent response is important, not the ability to process data, much less the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and respond with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so you will constantly use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be available for mass-produced cars in 10 years.
A further application option is to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
