The Elite in Danger
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote for the <0x24>700 billion rescue package proposed by the White House: a large part of the American public was more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is corroborated by yesterday’s New York Times, which reports that the current crisis has led to a break within the Republican Party, which is showing a growing division between the traditional, restrained approach to the East Coast that supports federal institutions and business circles and the growing new trend in the central and southern states that is anti-Washington and anti-financial world.
This direction was critically expressed in the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, this event is only one of the major changes that the ongoing economic transformation is predicting or predicting, not only in the United States, but in the entire Western world, and perhaps even beyond.
The crisis, both in the US and in Europe, seems to only accelerate the long-standing phenomena that are consolidating in this new atmosphere and finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is the re-update, the return to public awareness of the dual category of state sovereignty, in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis affects those banking and financial institutions that, although they have close ties with foreign countries, primarily, and on a fairly broad basis, attract people and families who live in a single country, a single state.
This, on the other hand, presents a direct political difficulty for those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are, by the way, also voters.
Thus, although the crisis seems to be global in economic terms, it is almost exclusively national in political terms.
It seems that political internationalism is essentially stranded: the European Union is a fine example of this, which is unable to establish a unified political direction between different interests and different national strategies.
So everyone expects intervention from the individual national governments, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules, but most of all the opening up of funds: because in times of need, only the individual states have economic resources, financial resources that can make things right.
They have the tools and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that are unlikely to be available to any other market or international organisation to such an extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on nation-statehood is fully in line with the fact that economic growth in recent times attaches increasing importance to a factor that is closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, the increasingly sophisticated technology, and that the global financial world was destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future was increasingly dependent on non-abstract things like water, crops, and oil.
From things that can be transported from one half of the planet to the other, yet they can be connected entirely to a demarcated place, to an area.
Thus, the one who controls the area has far more trump cards than the one who was unfortunately born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
This brings me to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of breaking line.
Whoever says territory, state, government, must also say politics, in other words leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis appears to be producing two mutually compatible phenomena:
On the one hand, an objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, someone who can handle events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially the economic leaders, who have proved to be completely incompetent and have proved that many of the areas ahead of them are still blurred, is a total loss of credit.
Together, the two are of even deeper significance and in a certain sense more disturbing: the feeling of loss of credibility, impatience, incompetence and separation that affects the entire leadership elite in an increasing number of Western countries.
It seems, therefore, that there is a growing belief among the population that the time of the social elite, which has hitherto reached its peak, has passed before their actions, their experiences, their way of life, their culture, in the complex sense of the word, have been adopted. This is increasingly alienating the social elite from the opinion of the majority.
In a word, the demand for leadership, in a veiled form, is fueling a wide-ranging but strong delegitimation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is perhaps manifested in the unanticipated “revolts” of voters against the Italians, or in recent times the sudden changes in public sentiment against the Americans. For example, the rise of the Conservatives to power in Austria and Bavaria, the work
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties, its programs and even it could be said that, along with its habits, its press and its renowned intellectuals, it is less and less able to represent what has been going on for some time in the deeper spheres of Western society.
In spite of all this, to speak frankly of “an imminent revolt of the masses” would be exaggerated.
But to keep your eyes open is not bad at all.
