The displacement of cinemas - the emergence of large, multi-room cinemas in the suburbs and, consequently, the atrophy of single-room cinemas in the city centers - is a process that seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time carries all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
When places full of history and memories disappear, "it's like going away with a friend, a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which twenty years ago won an Oscar and a grand prize at the Cannes Festival, perhaps after the lost of Tornatore, all tells the lyrical story of a small-town cinema, a yearning.
The data provided by the largest association of operators, Anec, is clear: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed. The biggest losses were recorded by cinemas in major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin, and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions, Emilia-Romagna leads, losing 82 single-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41) .
And that the proliferation of multiplexes is responsible for their disappearance is no better proof than the fact that these three regions of Italy have the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas: in the last five years, the number of rooms in Lombardy has increased by 195, in Tuscany by 81 and in Emilia-Romagna by the same amount.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says Anec president Paolo Protti. "It's okay to build new facilities, but the survival of the existing ones should also be ensured, because when an urban cinema closes, not everyone who goes there is willing to go into multiplexes.
Not to mention the unreserved funds to support operators: the state’s overdue debt is estimated at around EUR 10 million.
It is a disgrace, both ethically and morally, that the government does not abide by the laws in force.
It would require between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 million and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year to maintain the market.”
The case of Bologna deserves special attention: it is the first Italian city to have decided to address the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec, in order to protect and boost the one-room cinemas in the outer and downtown areas.
The provisions would include tax incentives for operators, as well as benefits for the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers can enter restricted areas and park at a reduced rate in certain parking areas.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, including other measures, will follow the example of Bologna.
But it is also certain that conventional cinemas, in order to be able to fight the rule of multiplexes, need to improve the sound and image quality, because the audience today is much more demanding.
Preserving traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and adolescence, gave me the spark that made me finally make Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, so when I walk the Via Nazionale in front of the closed Rialto or Quirinale, so as not to see the posters blackened by dust, I turn my head.
