The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones are coming
An inexhaustible source of energy that accounts for 70 percent of the planet’s surface and is only now being discovered by major international energy companies.
Waves, ocean currents, tides, all of these are renewable energy sources that giants like Chevron have been looking for, and now they're trying to get their hands on it.
For a hundred years, they have been researching how to extract energy from the movements of the sea. In the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research intensified.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of using offshore energy was set aside, but today the demands of environmental protection and the renewed rise in oil prices give the sector a new impetus.
In 2007, the London World Energy Council (WEC) estimated that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be met by installations that use waves in the sea.
This is twice as much as the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
The giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit to offshore energy and in 2005 signed an agreement to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolution when the signing was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are opting for marine energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies and is considering working with us," a spokesman for the US oil giant's associate company, the Wall Street Journal, said in a statement.
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit issued by the US Energy Commission to launch a marine energy project in Alaska.
This is a matter of great importance, especially considering the fact that the US is currently extracting oil in Alaska and that President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power are also on the path of offshore energy. The amounts invested so far, as far as details are known, show growing interest.
Technology is to be developed.
According to the experts, this is still a rudimentary technology, just because energy from the sea does not dispel any doubts about its environmental impact.
Existing installations, such as those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small in size, and therefore do not pose a major problem for the ecosystem.
In order to produce energy on a larger scale, however, we need installations with a greater environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a connected buoy system.
The thrusts generated by the waves and moving the buoys up and down are transformed into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure turns a turbine, which feeds a generator.
Electricity flows over subsea cables to land.
At the moment, there are four similar facilities in the design phase, which are still awaiting federal approval, and some of the energy generated will be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started generating power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six undersea turbines at the East River Strait in New York.
At tides, the movement of water rotates the blades of the turbines, and this rotational motion feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are just waiting for permissions to use energy.
Waves after tides.
At present, special attention should be paid to the opportunities that can be exploited through tides.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and can therefore be considered a more reliable source of energy.
